g.text: - 1m uploads per day, 100m views per day
- status [PROCESSING, READY] // PROCESSING means a transcoder is already
- creates a user entity, used during signup
- creates a video record and returns a presignedUrl to upload to
- gets video media (the raw audio/video itself)
- when a video is uploaded, two entities are created:
- Video - holds metadata for the video (name, description, etc)
- VideoInstance - refers to the specific bitrate/resolution combination of the originally uploaded video
- a VIDEO_CREATED message is published to a queue, the transcoding service listens and...
- fetches the originally uploaded video instance
- transcodes into multiple bitrates/resolutions, saves each copy back to object storage and creates
- client gets all VideoInstance DB records when fetching the Video metadata, can switch between
bitrates/resolutions as needed to optimize given its bandwidth
- most CDNs can likely handle streaming natively given a backing object store
- if not, fundamentally we want to allow downloading arbitrary chunks of the video parameterized by
- gives the client the ability to manage buffering, ie:
- as user watches video and buffer empties out, client can fetch t=20 to t=30, then t=30 to t=40, etc
- when new video is uploaded, a VIDEO_CREATED message is published.
Transcoding service subscribes, fetches the video from object storage (using a
link in the message payload), and transcodes it to other bitrates/resolutions.
It stores those back in object storage and creates VideoInstances for them.
When complete, it updates the Video object status to READY
- might make sense to publish a separate message per resolution/bitrate combo
